In [[agriculture]], '''disease management''' is the practice of minimising disease in crops to increase quantity or quality of harvest yield.

Organisms that cause infectious disease in crops include [[fungus|fungi]], [[oomycete]]s, [[bacteria]], [[plant virus|viruses]], [[viroid]]s, virus-like organisms, [[phytoplasma]]s, [[protozoa]], [[nematode]]s and [[parasitic plant]]s. Crops can also suffer from ectoparasites including [[insects]], [[mites]], [[snail]]s, [[slug]]s, and [[vertebrate]] animals, but these are not considered diseases.

