{{third-party|date=April 2017}} {{Infobox University |name = University of Kentucky College of Nursing |image = Uk logo.jpg |image_size = 150px| |established = 1960 |type = [[Public university|Public]] |dean = Janie Heath PhD, APRN-BC FAAN (interim) |city = [[Lexington, Kentucky|Lexington]] |state = [[Kentucky|KY]] |country = [[United States|USA]] |coor = {{Coord|38.0328|-84.5077|scale:3000|display=inline,title}} |enrollment = |staff= |website= [http://uknursing.uky.edu/ http://uknursing.uky.edu/] }}
The '''University of Kentucky College of Nursing''' is a [[nursing school]] in the [[University of Kentucky]]'s [[Chandler Medical Center]] in [[Lexington, KY]]. The address for the college is 751 Rose Street Lexington, KY 40536-0232.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uky.edu/nursing/ |title=College of Nursing &#124; see blue |publisher=Uky.edu |accessdate=April 24, 2017}}</ref> The University of Kentucky College of Nursing is titled full by the Kentucky Board of Nursing in their DNP Program, Master's Degree Nursing Leading to APRN, and Baccalaureate Degree programs. A full status is most desired, it means that the nursing program is in compliance with the Kentucky Board of Nursing.<ref>Kentucky Board of Nursing Program of Nursing Approval Status. (2015). KBN Connection, (44), 9.</ref> There are around 1,439 students enrolled in the College of Nursing and it is continuing to grow.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uky.edu/nursing/about-us/glance |title=At a Glance &#124; College of Nursing |publisher=Uky.edu |accessdate=April 24, 2017}}</ref> Nurses hold the largest division of healthcare providers; therefore, it is important to keep increasing the supply <ref>Snavely, T.M. (2016). Data Watch. A Brief Economic Analysis of the Looming Nursing Shortage in the United States. Nursing Economic$, 34(2), 98-100</ref>
==History== In 1957 there was a nursing shortage so William R. Willard, the dean of the Albert b. Chandler Medical Center, suggested a college of nursing. The UK College of Nursing was then founded in 1960. Marcia Dake, EdD, RN was the first dean of the college. Marcia was then joined with three other women to help teach the college. The first undergraduate class consisted of 35 women and they graduated in 1964. A [[Master of Science in Nursing]] program was added in 1969, followed by a [[PhD in nursing]] program in 1987. In 2001 the college established the nation's first [[Doctor of Nursing Practice]] program, which eventually led to a discontinuation of the masters program. Lastly, in 2010 the college celebrated its 50th anniversary.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uky.edu/nursing/about-us/welcome-college-nursing/history |title=History &#124; College of Nursing |publisher=Uky.edu |accessdate=April 24, 2017}}</ref>
